Death is called an uncloathing,2 Cor. 5.4. becauſe it will ſtrip you of all your places of honour, of all the ornaments of nature;
As ye came naked into the World, Job 1. ult.
ſo ye muſt go naked out of the World. Nothing will follow you when ye die but your works. Rev. 14.13. When the good Magiſtrate dyeth that hath been zealous for the Lord's honour, and ſtudious of his ſouls welfare; his works follow him through free grace, into an eternal weight of glory. When the evil Magiſtrate dyeth, who hath been careleſs of his Conſcience, and unfaithful in his calling, his works follow him through divine ſeverity, into a boundleſs Ocean of endleſs miſery.

As the fineſt garment breedeth a moth, and that moth eateth up the garment;
                  Phyſitians have a rule, 
                  Ʋltimus ſanitatis gradus, eſt morbo proximus. As the ſtrongeſt tree breedeth a Worm, and that Worm devoureth the tree: So the faireſt and ſtrongeſt bodies breed ſuch diſeaſes as will at laſt conſume them.

